  "prompt": "How do I create a customized ISO like CS50?",
  "response": "To create a customized ISO similar to CS50's, you can follow these general steps:\n\n1. Choose a Base Distribution\n- Start with a Linux distribution (Ubuntu is common)\n- Download the official ISO\n\n2. Prepare Your Development Environment\n- Install virtualization software like VirtualBox or VMware\n- Create a VM with the base ISO\n\n3. Customize the Installation\na) During Installation:\n- Set up custom user accounts\n- Configure basic settings\n- Partition the disk as needed\n\nb) Post-Installation Configuration:\n- Update the system\n```bash\nsudo apt update\nsudo apt upgrade\n```\n\n4. Install Required Software\n```bash\nsudo apt install build-essential\nsudo apt install python3 python3-pip\nsudo apt install gcc\nsudo apt install git\nsudo apt install code  # VS Code\nsudo apt install clang\nsudo apt install valgrind\n```\n\n5. Configure Development Tools\n- Set up custom shell configurations\n- Install additional development libraries\n- Configure IDE settings\n\n6. Create Custom Scripts\n- Develop initialization and setup scripts\n- Create custom aliases and functions\n\n7. Generate ISO\nUse tools like:\n- Cubic (Ubuntu)\n- Remastersys\n- Live-build\n\nExample Cubic Process:\n- Install Cubic\n```bash\nsudo apt-add-repository ppa:cubic-wizard/release\nsudo apt update\nsudo apt install cubic\n```\n- Follow Cubic's GUI wizard to create custom ISO\n\n8. Test Your Custom ISO\n- Boot from created ISO\n- Verify all configurations work correctly\n\nDetailed CS50-specific recommendations would require more context about exact requirements.\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any specific aspect of ISO customization?",
